entry.title: Revert "[gc] Make FontFamily immutable."
entry.content:
This reverts commit ca3d3085d8b01fc74623d639c615fc57842cd26d.



Reason for revert: crrev.com/c/5328767 is the reason for failure on some tests on MSAN. Please see crbug.com/327969288 for more details.



Original change's description:

> [gc] Make FontFamily immutable.

>

> Previously we'd build up font-family lists front to back, but would

> need to mutate them to do so. Instead just build them backwards.

>

> This removes a bunch of problematic APIs (like AppendFamily - which

> doesn't append), and simplifies the code.

>

> This will help avoid atomic write barriers once converted to oilpan.

entry.title: Fix Lacros Picker insertion.
entry.content:
Lacros input fields have an oddity: input type is not guaranteed to

be correct synchronously, but it is guaranteed to be correct

*eventually*.



We currently assumed that the input type is always correct when

the focus changes, but this is wrong for Lacros. Therefore, instead

of immediately giving up when an insertion has failed, we wait

until the full insert timeout before giving up.



This actually aligns with the behaviour of the other checks in

the insertion (such as checking if the type is NONE), where they

don't fail immediately.



This logic definitely is more consistent and robust.



Follow up needed to add test coverage for Lacros.

entry.title: [odfs] Check the ODFS extension exists before using it
entry.content:
ODFS was first added to the IsBuiltinComponent() check in

http://crrev.com/c/4780041 to allow ODFS console logs to be included in

Chrome logs.



Previously it was assumed that if IsBuiltinComponent() was called for

the ODFS extension, that it would be found with a

GetInstalledExtension(kODFSExtensionId) call. However, it appears there

is a race condition upon startup where the extension can be installed

but not yet appear in the extension registry.



It is safer to first check that GetInstalledExtension(kODFSExtensionId)

returns a non-null extension before accessing its location(). In the

worst case, the returned extension is null and the ODFS log does not

get included in the Chrome logs.

entry.title: [text-spacing-trim] Stop assuming offset 0 is safe-to-break
entry.content:
This patch stops `ShapeResult` to assume the offset 0 is

always safe-to-break.



It was an micro-optimization in the legacy engine, where the

first glyph of an output from HarfBuzz is safe-to-break.



NG shapes across elements and splits a `ShapeResult` into

multiple `ShapeResult`s. In that case, the first glyph of a

`ShapeResult` may not be safe-to-break.



Two relevant fixes:

* Fix `HanKerning` didn't add a synthesized unsafe-t-break for

the first glyph because it wasn't used.

* Fix how `AddUnsafeToBreak` computes run-local offset when

the start index isn't 0.



Fixed: 326903564

entry.title: Make sure that the inert element and its subtree cannot be searchable
entry.content:
As per the HTML spec:

Content in an inert element and its subtree will not be perceivable

by all users, or interactive.



Consider this test case:



Do not find me please




The return value of `window.find('me')` is true, but `div` is

non-interactive due to the inert attribute being assigned to it.

`ShouldIgnoreContents` should assess the inert attribute of the element.

The reason why some cases in `inert/inert-and-find.html` cannot be

passed is also attributed to this factor.

entry.title: MediaApp a11y: Implement ViewportUpdated(), and related a11y actions.
entry.content:
This method is called from the MediaApp SWA (also known as Gallery),

when the viewport of a PDF changes.

Meanwhile, assistive software can change the viewport using

a handful of accessibility actions, such as "ScrollIntoView".



This patch implements the Mojo plumbing for "ViewportUpdated" and demonstrates how accessibility

actions will be able to change the viewport.



More information about the security implications are in the design doc found at:

https://goto.corp.google.com/bl-pdf-ocr/
